### std::map

`std::map` is an associative container that stores key-value pairs in sorted order by key. It is typically implemented as a balanced binary search tree (red-black tree).

---

### Declaration and Initialization

```cpp
#include <map>

map<string, int> ages;

ages["Alice"] = 30;
ages["Bob"] = 25;
ages["Charlie"] = 35;

// Initializer list (C++11)
map<string, int> scores = {{"Alice", 95}, {"Bob", 87}};
```

---

### Common Operations

| Operation | Code | Description |
|-----------|------|-------------|
| Insert | `m[key] = value;` or `m.insert({k, v});` | Add or update |
| Access | `m.at(key);` | Access with bounds checking |
| Find | `m.find(key);` | Returns iterator or `end()` |
| Erase | `m.erase(key);` | Remove by key |
| Check | `m.count(key);` | 0 or 1 (unique keys) |
| Size | `m.size();` | Number of elements |
| Empty | `m.empty();` | Check if empty |

---

### Iterating

```cpp
for (const auto& pair : myMap) {
  cout << pair.first << ": " << pair.second << endl;
}

// With structured bindings (C++17)
for (const auto& [key, value] : myMap) {
  cout << key << ": " << value << endl;
}
```

---

### unordered_map

For O(1) average lookups (hash table):

```cpp
#include <unordered_map>

unordered_map<string, int> hash;
hash["key"] = 42;
```

---

> **Key Point:** `std::map` maintains sorted order with O(log n) operations. For unsorted data with faster average access, use `std::unordered_map` (hash table, C++11).

codeExample:
#include <iostream>
#include <map>
using namespace std;

int main() {
  map<string, double> prices;

  prices["apple"] = 0.99;
  prices["banana"] = 0.59;
  prices["orange"] = 0.79;

  for (const auto& [item, price] : prices) {
    cout << item << ": $" << price << endl;
  }

  string search = "apple";
  if (prices.count(search)) {
    cout << search << " costs $" << prices[search] << endl;
  }
  return 0;
}
